{\"video_title\": \"Prompt Patterns\", \"transcript\": \"вЂ‹Patterns in our prompts can tap into powerful behavior within the large вЂ‹language model. вЂ‹It's trained on all these different patterns. вЂ‹And it gets really good at using the patterns in our language and вЂ‹our prompt to decide what it's going to do. вЂ‹So one of the important things that we're going to learn about is the concept of вЂ‹a prompt pattern. вЂ‹A pattern for structuring the words and the statements in your prompt. вЂ‹So what is a prompt pattern? вЂ‹A prompt pattern is a way that we document a certain structure of phrases and вЂ‹statements in order to solve a particular problem in with a large language model. вЂ‹So we'd like to interact with a large language model and вЂ‹we'd like to solve a particular problem. вЂ‹And so a prompt pattern is basically a way of structuring our statements, вЂ‹a pattern for structuring our statements to use the large language model to вЂ‹solve that particular problem. вЂ‹So what would be an example of this? вЂ‹Well, let's imagine that we wanted to consistently вЂ‹generate the words lamb, its fleece was as white as snow. вЂ‹Well, a pattern could be any time you need lamb, вЂ‹it's fleece was white as snow you can write the statement Mary had a little, вЂ‹you will very consistently get lamb, it's fleece was as white as snow as the output. вЂ‹And so for example, we can go and we can rerun this lamb, вЂ‹it's fleece was as white as snow. вЂ‹We get more or less behavior. вЂ‹But if we want to consistently get those next words generated, вЂ‹we can do it over and over and over again through Mary had a little, вЂ‹it gives us some control over the output. вЂ‹It gives us a consistent somewhat behavior. вЂ‹Now it's not perfectly consistent, there's variations in the output. вЂ‹And we've seen in all of these examples, we've got variation in what happened, but вЂ‹we did get some consistency in the behavior. вЂ‹So what a prompt pattern is, it's a way for us to document and вЂ‹talk about certain structures of our language, series of statements and вЂ‹wording that then will help us solve some particular problem. вЂ‹If the problem that we need to solve is we need to get lamb it's fleece as white as вЂ‹snow as the next several words that are produced. вЂ‹Then this is the pattern we use. вЂ‹Now in many cases, we might have specific words we want. вЂ‹For example, we may want the large language model to tell us yes or no. вЂ‹We may want it to summarize something, we may want it to ask us questions. вЂ‹We may want it to always include certain things in its output. вЂ‹All of these things are problems that you might want to solve. вЂ‹We might want to know how do we make sure it always includes these things and вЂ‹its output? вЂ‹How do we make sure that its output is always formatted in a particular way? вЂ‹How do we try to make sure or вЂ‹get more consistent behavior on only getting a yes or a no. вЂ‹These are types of problems that you might want to solve by changing the pattern вЂ‹of our prompt basically the structure of our prompt. вЂ‹Now going back to our intuitive sort of understanding of prompts, вЂ‹you can see why thinking about it in terms of power patterns is powerful because вЂ‹patterns are basically that are in our prompt are tapping into things вЂ‹that the large language model has been trained on. вЂ‹It's been trained to predict the next word over and вЂ‹over and it's learned certain patterns from the words. вЂ‹And if we can format our prompt in a way that taps into those patterns вЂ‹that's learned, we're more likely to get the behavior we want and вЂ‹solve that particular problem. вЂ‹So we document the pattern and вЂ‹the structure of our prompt in order to solve a particular problem that we need or вЂ‹generate a particular behavior that we need for the large language model. вЂ‹So we're going to go through in a series of lectures throughout this course вЂ‹of specific prompt patterns that we can use within the context of вЂ‹large language models to solve important problems.\"}